It wasn't even a real show.

32:51.560 --> 32:53.519
You were just, like,
in the middle of a soccer field.

32:53.520 --> 32:55.879
It was a traveling production.

32:55.880 --> 32:59.079
And it was really fucking
thrilling to watch.

32:59.080 --> 33:02.948
'Cause you loved words.
You loved poetry.

33:06.640 --> 33:10.383
But I do remember it
kinda made me feel sad.

33:10.880 --> 33:12.506
Why?

33:13.200 --> 33:15.119
Honey, I want to support you.

33:15.120 --> 33:16.999
I really do believe in you.

33:17.000 --> 33:20.559
Why did seeing me love
Shakespeare make you sad?

33:20.560 --> 33:22.199
I don't know.

33:22.200 --> 33:24.839
I was terrified that
I'd never ever find

33:24.840 --> 33:26.439
that kind of passion in my life.

33:26.440 --> 33:28.271
And the truth is, I haven't.

33:29.760 --> 33:33.799
I input data into a spreadsheet.

33:33.800 --> 33:35.999
Literally, a scanner
should be doing my job,

33:36.000 --> 33:38.879
and there's just too much bureaucracy
for anyone to even notice.

33:38.880 --> 33:41.399
One day you're gonna be running
that whole fucking place.

33:41.400 --> 33:43.599
I don't want to run the
fucking water department.

33:43.600 --> 33:45.959
Then what do you want to do?
I don't even know.

33:45.960 --> 33:47.279
I don't know. And you know what?

33:47.280 --> 33:49.359
I don't have a second
to figure it out,

33:49.360 --> 33:51.319
because I'm on a fucking treadmill.

33:51.320 --> 33:55.279
And if I stop, our kids don't eat.

33:55.280 --> 33:57.748
And it's all on me.

33:59.480 --> 34:01.639
I just...

34:01.640 --> 34:03.599
I thought you supported my dream.

34:03.600 --> 34:05.670
You said you supported my dream.

34:05.920 --> 34:07.959
When did this relationship become

34:07.960 --> 34:11.304
solely about supporting your dream?

34:21.639 --> 34:23.426
Hello?

34:24.480 --> 34:26.186
Yes?

34:28.800 --> 34:30.745
Oh, my God.

34:38.400 --> 34:41.266
Dr. Becker, what happened?

34:42.400 --> 34:44.359
I told him the new-age
treatment was nonsense,

34:44.360 --> 34:46.799
but desperate people
will try anything.

34:46.800 --> 34:47.918
It didn't work?

34:47.920 --> 34:50.039
The cancer's progressed.

34:50.040 --> 34:52.518
He's having paraneoplastic symptoms,

34:52.520 --> 34:54.119
his liver's beginning to fail.

34:54.120 --> 34:55.478
Can we see him?

34:55.480 --> 34:59.905
Well, he's sleeping, but he's
right in here in ICU. Come.

35:31.800 --> 35:34.359
Okay, okay, let's just calm down.

35:34.360 --> 35:36.439
What are you talking about, Noah?
Why would we not be calm?

35:36.440 --> 35:37.999
Look, before you freak out,

35:38.000 --> 35:39.399
I still get the Death Star.

35:39.400 --> 35:41.061
What's happening, Noah?

35:41.200 --> 35:42.919
This.

35:42.920 --> 35:45.946
- Oh, my God!
- What the fuck!

35:46.120 --> 35:49.599
I am tired of you guys
not listening to me.

35:49.600 --> 35:52.719
I just want to go back to
yeshiva and be with my friends,

35:52.720 --> 35:54.399
and I am sick and tired of Tucker

35:54.400 --> 35:56.550
always teasing me about Jesse.

35:56.880 --> 35:59.879
Now everyone will know who I am.

35:59.880 --> 36:01.519
So you shaved your head?

36:01.520 --> 36:03.039
Sweetie, your beautiful hair.

36:03.040 --> 36:04.559
Your beautiful hair.

36:04.560 --> 36:09.239
You said that I would still be
pretty even if I shaved my head!

36:09.240 --> 36:11.119
- What?
- No, completely out of context.

36:11.120 --> 36:12.239
What are you talking about?

36:12.240 --> 36:14.399
I was talking about the
Orthodox wig thing.

36:14.400 --> 36:15.879
This is not what I was talking about.

36:15.880 --> 36:18.679
I was just innocently playing
video games with the boy when...

36:18.680 --> 36:20.079
- Tucker!
- Tucker, great kid.

36:20.080 --> 36:21.279
Really a lot smarter
than I thought...

36:21.280 --> 36:22.799
- You let her shave her fucking head?
- No, no!

36:22.800 --> 36:24.399
You know, they were just
having their normal banter.

36:24.400 --> 36:25.759
I certainly didn't think that

36:25.760 --> 36:27.919
she was gonna come out looking
like fucking Sinead O'Connor.

36:27.920 --> 36:28.959
Okay, I shouldn't cry, right?

36:28.960 --> 36:30.559
- No, don't cry. It's just hair.
- 'Cause it's just hair.

36:30.560 --> 36:32.119
It'll grow back in, like, a year.

36:32.120 --> 36:33.199
- Go to your room!
- What's going on?

36:33.200 --> 36:34.759
- Don't go to your room.
- Go in the house!

36:34.760 --> 36:36.559
- I'll go to your room.
- Go in the house!

36:36.560 --> 36:39.159
- Go inside.
- Feel better. Feel better, kiddo.

36:39.160 --> 36:40.999
And you get the fuck out of here.

36:41.000 --> 36:43.599
What about our little Lego situation?

36:43.600 --> 36:47.279
My child shaved her head
while you were babysitting.

36:47.280 --> 36:48.759
You think you're getting
a Lego Death Star?

36:48.760 --> 36:50.119
You're out of your fucking mind.

36:50.120 --> 36:51.319
You're a fucking Indian giver.

36:51.320 --> 36:52.479
You're a piece of shit Indian giver.

36:52.480 --> 36:53.999
And by the way, do you know
where I just came from?

36:54.000 --> 36:56.519
Your father lying
comatose in the hospital

36:56.520 --> 36:59.999
with wires and veins and
the thing in his nose.

37:00.000 --> 37:01.679
I thought he was on some sort of...

37:01.680 --> 37:04.639
No, the treatment didn't work, man.
He's dying for real, okay?

37:04.640 --> 37:05.799
How long does he have?

37:05.800 --> 37:07.159
I don't know, but the fact
that you're asking that,

37:07.160 --> 37:08.519
what, are you gonna procrastinate?

37:08.520 --> 37:10.759
Cancer means dying, Noah,
and you need to wake up,

37:10.760 --> 37:13.831
because life is happening
all around you.

37:20.240 --> 37:21.319
Oh.

37:21.320 --> 37:23.719
Nice to see you, Mr. Bloom.

37:23.720 --> 37:25.959
Sorry it's under such
difficult circumstances.

37:25.960 --> 37:27.621
I have something for you.

37:28.760 --> 37:30.799
Sorry to throw all
of this at you now.

37:30.800 --> 37:34.349
It does have to be dealt with
sooner rather than later.

37:42.640 --> 37:47.225
He's very sick. Counsel the actor.

38:23.560 --> 38:28.987
Come over here.
Don't be fooled by all this.

38:29.800 --> 38:33.827
It's all to cover their
asses so nobody gets sued.

38:34.760 --> 38:36.500
I'm fine.

38:43.920 --> 38:45.479
So, Dad, I'm confused.

38:45.480 --> 38:48.599
You said there was this
experimental treatment.

38:50.320 --> 38:53.479
They told me from the beginning

38:53.480 --> 38:56.267
it doesn't work for everyone.

38:57.120 --> 38:58.919
I rolled the dice.

38:58.920 --> 39:01.759
But did Dr. Becker give
you any new information?

39:01.760 --> 39:03.359
Did he say anything about...

39:03.360 --> 39:06.545
A few months. Maybe a year.

39:07.800 --> 39:11.144
Or as long as it takes
them to finish the 405.

39:13.120 --> 39:16.351
If I died every time he
said I was gonna die,

39:16.760 --> 39:20.742
I'd have more lives than
Shirley MacLaine. Jesus.

39:22.520 --> 39:24.670
Did you see that pitch?

39:25.960 --> 39:29.589
If Collins doesn't pull a new
pitcher out of the bullpen soon,

39:30.200 --> 39:32.782
I'm gonna yank all these tubes
and jump out the window.

39:36.240 --> 39:38.902
Hey, is there any water over there?

39:39.320 --> 39:41.424
Yeah.

40:39.040 --> 40:41.383
You okay?

40:42.200 --> 40:43.861
Yeah.

40:44.640 --> 40:46.710
I mean, I guess, no.

40:49.280 --> 40:50.759
It's funny, you spend your whole life

40:50.760 --> 40:52.159
hoping it'll all mean something,

40:52.160 --> 40:54.839
and ultimately it
really comes down to

40:54.840 --> 40:57.719
one question in a
neatly folded pamphlet.

40:57.720 --> 41:01.159
How should we deal with your bones?

41:01.160 --> 41:04.550
Honey, maybe you shouldn't
be looking at that right now.

41:07.560 --> 41:09.186
How are the kids?

41:10.440 --> 41:12.319
Scared.

41:12.320 --> 41:13.821
Yeah.

41:13.960 --> 41:15.039
I just always imagined

41:15.040 --> 41:19.386
I'd have a better handle on what
I believed by the time we had kids.

41:19.600 --> 41:21.319
And we got pregnant so young,

41:21.320 --> 41:23.319
and now I have these
little faces looking up

41:23.320 --> 41:25.279
at me and I don't know what to say.

41:25.280 --> 41:27.319
I know, I'm with you. Fuck if I know

41:27.320 --> 41:29.231
what we're supposed to be doing here.

41:29.400 --> 41:32.949
As parents or on Earth?

41:35.080 --> 41:36.239
Can I say both?

41:44.400 --> 41:48.746
Gracie, wake up, sleepyhead.

41:51.440 --> 41:52.879
What's going on?

41:52.880 --> 41:55.621
We're going on a field trip.

41:55.840 --> 41:59.423
I made you a bowl
of cereal, but I ate it.

43:44.080 --> 43:47.186
Is Grandpa gonna die?

43:49.000 --> 43:51.239
It looks that way, sweetie.

43:51.240 --> 43:55.062
Are we gonna bury him in
the backyard with Whiskers?

43:55.600 --> 43:58.399
Oh, buddy, I don't think
we're allowed to do that.

43:58.400 --> 44:02.159
We're gonna have to ask
Grandpa what he wants.

44:02.160 --> 44:06.904
I think he'll want
to be with Whiskers.

44:25.000 --> 44:27.582
All right, guys, here we are.

44:31.320 --> 44:34.999
Follow me.

44:35.000 --> 44:36.239
Shouldn't we set up our camp?

44:36.240 --> 44:37.719
We'll do it later. This way.

44:37.720 --> 44:38.799
What are we doing out here?

44:38.800 --> 44:41.479
I'm showing you one of the
coolest places on Earth.

44:41.480 --> 44:43.079
I'll race you to the top.

44:43.080 --> 44:45.919
Wow! Look at those legs!

44:45.920 --> 44:50.199
Lookit, the little legs are fastest!

44:50.200 --> 44:54.102
This is it. This is the spot.

44:54.760 --> 44:56.119
What is it?

44:56.120 --> 44:57.959
This is the spot where I
had one of the deepest,

44:57.960 --> 45:01.111
most sincere, spiritual
moments of my life.

45:01.960 --> 45:04.701
The last time I had an epiphany,
it was right here.

45:04.800 --> 45:06.426
What's an "aniffany"?

45:06.800 --> 45:10.639
An epiphany is when
you realize something

45:10.640 --> 45:13.319
that you really needed to realize.

45:13.320 --> 45:16.959
You know, sometimes in life
you can get kinda stuck

45:16.960 --> 45:19.359
and you feel like you should
have changed chapters by now,

45:19.360 --> 45:22.147
but you can't.

45:22.520 --> 45:26.559
Are you stuck because
Grandpa's dying?

45:26.560 --> 45:29.559
Am I stuck because Grandpa's dying?

45:29.560 --> 45:30.759
Uh, yeah.

45:30.760 --> 45:33.119
I think that's one of the reasons.

45:33.120 --> 45:36.305
And because you haven't worked
since that dandruff commercial?

45:36.560 --> 45:38.903
That's in there, too.
Thanks for reminding me.

45:41.600 --> 45:42.839
Well, the sun went down.

45:42.840 --> 45:44.119
What do you guys say,
should we make a fire?

45:44.120 --> 45:45.159
Yeah.

45:45.160 --> 45:46.821
All right, let's do it.

45:54.000 --> 45:56.229
Help him out, Grace, help him out.

45:57.440 --> 45:59.988
Will Grandpa be able to
see us when he dies?

46:01.440 --> 46:04.279
I don't know, buddy. I don't know.

46:04.280 --> 46:07.181
Nobody knows what
happens when you die.

46:07.440 --> 46:11.706
There's as many opinions
as there are people.

46:12.520 --> 46:16.502
And some people will tell you with
absolute certainty they know.

46:16.680 --> 46:18.545
But they're wrong?

46:19.520 --> 46:23.479
No. No, I'm not saying they're wrong.

46:23.480 --> 46:26.062
Right now I kinda
feel like they're lucky.

46:26.840 --> 46:29.183
'Cause the rest of us, until we

46:29.520 --> 46:32.119
see something that makes sense,

46:32.120 --> 46:36.159
until we hear something we believe,

46:36.160 --> 46:39.550
we're kinda left with nothing.

46:40.080 --> 46:41.359
Tell us a ghost story.

46:41.360 --> 46:43.399
I don't know any
ghost stories. Do you?

46:43.400 --> 46:44.559
I'll think about it.

46:44.560 --> 46:45.599
All right, you think on it.

46:45.600 --> 46:47.119
I can think of one, too.

46:47.120 --> 46:49.519
I know they usually end
with someone has a claw.

46:51.520 --> 46:52.759
I could tell you something Grandma

46:52.760 --> 46:54.039
used to say to me when I went to bed.

46:54.040 --> 46:55.079
How about that?

46:55.080 --> 46:56.199
- Okay.
- All right.

46:56.200 --> 46:58.065
I remember a little bit.

46:59.440 --> 47:03.239
"And indeed there will be time

47:03.240 --> 47:06.903
"For the yellow smoke that
slides along the street

47:06.920 --> 47:10.839
"Rubbing its back
upon the window panes

47:10.840 --> 47:12.580
"There will be time

47:14.040 --> 47:15.239
"There will be time

47:15.240 --> 47:19.301
"To prepare a face to meet
the faces that you meet

47:19.800 --> 47:22.428
"There will be time
to murder and create

47:25.920 --> 47:28.679
"And time for all the
works and days of hands

47:28.680 --> 47:33.629
"That lift and drop a
question on your plate

47:34.800 --> 47:39.385
"Time for you and time for me

47:41.120 --> 47:43.588
"And time yet for 100 indecisions

47:44.840 --> 47:47.999
"And for 100 visions and revisions

47:48.000 --> 47:53.791
"Before the taking
of a toast and tea"

48:03.680 --> 48:05.279
Wake up, sleepyheads.

48:05.280 --> 48:07.270
It's time for school.

48:11.680 --> 48:13.944
Did you have an epiphany?

48:14.480 --> 48:19.542
No. But I did have
a really good idea.

48:24.960 --> 48:28.599
You can pick any one you want.

48:28.600 --> 48:30.590
- Any one?
- Any one.

48:31.040 --> 48:35.670
Just as long as it is unique
and amazing like you.

49:05.080 --> 49:06.945
Oh, hey, pal. Come on in.

49:07.080 --> 49:08.581
Oh!

49:08.840 --> 49:12.389
Just watching this kitten video
on YouTube. This kitten is crazy.

49:13.040 --> 49:14.799
Sorry, can I talk to
you about something?

49:14.800 --> 49:18.907
Sure. Come on in. Have a seat.
What's on your mind?

49:19.960 --> 49:21.959
It's just that I'm
having some trouble

49:21.960 --> 49:25.039
getting used to my cubicle partner.

49:25.040 --> 49:28.544
- Jerry? But he's hilarious.
- Yeah.

49:29.600 --> 49:35.425
It's just that he's a
little inappropriate and...

49:36.480 --> 49:37.959
I know I'm relatively new here.

49:37.960 --> 49:41.639
So I don't want to ruffle
anyone's status quo.

49:41.640 --> 49:43.439
But I think it's time I let you know

49:43.440 --> 49:46.039
that he's making me uncomfortable.

49:46.040 --> 49:47.999
Okay, so what did he say?

49:48.000 --> 49:52.119
Well, he started with saying that

49:52.120 --> 49:54.270
when he's not wearing any underwear,

49:55.440 --> 50:00.119
that he gets these
little half-boners.

50:00.120 --> 50:01.621
Mmm-hmm.

50:02.240 --> 50:04.159
He also made it talk to me.

50:04.160 --> 50:05.359
Who?

50:05.360 --> 50:07.199
His half-boner.

50:07.200 --> 50:08.799
Well, what did it sound like?

50:08.800 --> 50:14.279
I don't know.
It's like a high-pitched...

50:14.280 --> 50:17.919
Like a ghost voice.

50:17.920 --> 50:22.319
Okay, but he didn't do a black
guy voice or anything, did he?

50:22.320 --> 50:24.026
He didn't do anything racial?

50:24.280 --> 50:25.959
No, it was high-pitched.

50:25.960 --> 50:28.559
- Good.
- Like a mouse.

50:28.560 --> 50:30.599
Or, like I said, a ghost.

50:30.600 --> 50:32.279
Like a ghost mouse.

50:32.280 --> 50:33.799
Sure.

50:33.800 --> 50:35.799
Okay, okay. Look, Sarah,

50:35.800 --> 50:37.279
I know we don't always run things

50:37.280 --> 50:38.599
according to the book around here,

50:38.600 --> 50:41.519
but I think you need
to lighten up a little bit.

50:41.520 --> 50:43.199
Nobody's trying to touch you.

50:43.200 --> 50:46.079
No one's making their
penis talk like a rapper.

50:46.080 --> 50:50.079
So, I'll tell you what. I am going
to move Jerry out of your cubicle

50:50.080 --> 50:51.639
and I'm also gonna tell him
to tone it down a notch.

50:51.640 --> 50:55.639
But you need to promise
to smile a little more.

50:55.640 --> 50:58.347
You know, a little bit
more Hakuna matata.

50:58.480 --> 51:00.639
I don't know what that means.

51:00.640 --> 51:03.319
It means, "No worries for
the rest of your days."

51:03.320 --> 51:05.399
No, I have two children,
I know it's from The Lion King.

51:05.400 --> 51:08.639
I just don't understand how that
applies to the water department.

51:08.640 --> 51:12.079
It means that you need to
lighten up a little bit, Sarah.

51:12.080 --> 51:14.662
You've got something
everybody else wants.

51:16.480 --> 51:17.999
Remind me what that is.

51:18.000 --> 51:20.025
A job.

51:21.880 --> 51:24.906
Right.

51:29.080 --> 51:31.839
Well, I guess technically this
could qualify as art class.

51:31.840 --> 51:33.159
Hey, bud, make sure you're cutting

51:33.160 --> 51:34.799
along the lines here
that I drew, okay?

51:34.800 --> 51:37.399
That's for the chest piece.
It's very special.

51:37.400 --> 51:39.199
Aren't you a little old
for playing dress-up?

51:39.200 --> 51:40.759
It's hardly playing dress-up, Aidan.

51:40.760 --> 51:43.119
It's for Comic-Con.
The top prize is $1,000.

51:43.120 --> 51:45.679
Not to mention the chance for
some congratulatory poontang

51:45.680 --> 51:47.479
from a super-hot Furry I just met.

51:47.480 --> 51:48.519
What's poontang?

51:48.520 --> 51:49.679
It's what the astronauts drink.

51:49.680 --> 51:51.559
- Can I have some poontang?
- One day.

51:51.560 --> 51:52.879
It's only available in space.

51:52.880 --> 51:54.506
Damn it.

51:56.480 --> 51:58.879
So, hey, we're gonna meet
up at my house around 6:30

51:58.880 --> 52:00.199
and then we'll go see Dad, okay?

52:00.200 --> 52:03.199
Oh, yeah, right. I've been meaning
to talk to you about that, Aidan.

52:03.200 --> 52:06.039
You know, I got a ton of work
here and plus, I'm not going.

52:06.040 --> 52:07.279
What?

52:07.280 --> 52:10.319
Dude, what's the point?
I haven't seen him for, like, a year.

52:10.320 --> 52:11.879
I guess my tolerance for being called

52:11.880 --> 52:13.399
a disappointment has
an expiration date.

52:13.400 --> 52:15.839
You haven't spoken to Dad in a year?

52:15.840 --> 52:18.159
No. The last time he called
me was on my birthday.

52:18.160 --> 52:21.719
I think my present was a
20-minute thesis on why I suck.

52:21.720 --> 52:24.109
So you're just gonna cut him off.

52:24.440 --> 52:26.879
Dude, you gotta see this
from my perspective, okay?

52:26.880 --> 52:30.159
You at least have
a wife and a family.

52:30.160 --> 52:33.119
When he looks at me,
all he sees is failure.

52:33.120 --> 52:34.679
Well, what about Grandma?

52:34.680 --> 52:39.239
No. My mom believed in me.

52:39.240 --> 52:40.839
With her, things were different.

52:40.840 --> 52:42.799
She at least made
him a tad bit nicer.

52:42.800 --> 52:44.879
But with my dad...

52:44.880 --> 52:47.826
Nope, never gave him any
reason to be proud of me.

52:48.280 --> 52:50.225
All right, let's try it on.

52:56.560 --> 52:59.199
Well, what do you think?

52:59.200 --> 53:00.861
- So cool.
- Awesome!

53:01.560 --> 53:03.266
Aidan?

53:07.800 --> 53:11.429
We both spent our entire lives
wishing we could be something great.

53:11.440 --> 53:13.599
And now we're finally
called upon to do something

53:13.600 --> 53:17.229
that requires some actual
bravery and you run and hide.

53:18.360 --> 53:23.719
You know what the problem with
hiding in a fish bowl is, Noah?

53:23.720 --> 53:25.631
Everyone can see you.

53:26.920 --> 53:29.900
Come on, guys. Let's go see Grandpa.

53:31.400 --> 53:33.823
Grace, come on.

53:33.920 --> 53:37.279
Bye, Uncle Noah. I love you.

53:37.280 --> 53:41.421
All right. Thanks. Thank you.

53:58.600 --> 54:01.399
I'm lost in balloons.
Right in here. Right in...

54:01.400 --> 54:04.519
Look who it is, Grandpa!

54:04.520 --> 54:06.039
Give Grandpa a hug.

54:06.040 --> 54:09.319
Hey. Thank you.

54:09.320 --> 54:10.679
Got you some balloons.

54:10.680 --> 54:12.639
Mommy will put those in the corner.

54:12.640 --> 54:14.187
I'll take those.

54:17.720 --> 54:19.221
What's wrong, Dad?

54:19.280 --> 54:20.879
What'd these hippies do to your hair?

54:20.880 --> 54:23.719
Oh, it's just temporary dye, Dad.
She was just having a little fun.

54:23.720 --> 54:24.839
- Right, Gracie?
- Yeah.

54:24.840 --> 54:27.866
Looks like you work in the
world's oldest profession.

54:28.520 --> 54:30.199
What's the world's oldest profession?

54:30.200 --> 54:33.399
Being an angel was the
very first job there was.

54:33.400 --> 54:35.106
Beautiful angel.

54:35.400 --> 54:37.439
I am your angel, Grandpa.

54:37.440 --> 54:39.879
I daven a healing prayer
for you three times a day.

54:39.880 --> 54:42.030
- Once in the morning, once...
- Grandpa!

54:42.320 --> 54:43.839
I bought you a fart buzzer.

54:43.840 --> 54:45.199
What's a fart buzzer?

54:45.200 --> 54:46.519
It's this thing.

54:46.520 --> 54:47.839
You press different buttons

54:47.840 --> 54:50.079
and it makes different
funny fart noises.

54:50.080 --> 54:51.959
You may choose any
fart you would like.

54:51.960 --> 54:54.799
I choose for you the Ripper.

55:02.880 --> 55:05.542
Oh, I see the
homeschooling's going well.

55:07.080 --> 55:09.319
Tucker, do you know
your times tables yet?

55:09.320 --> 55:11.639
No. But I know this.

55:13.080 --> 55:15.519
I don't know if Grandpa's a
big fan of the fart buzzer.

55:15.520 --> 55:17.279
- I'm gonna take the fart buzzer.
- Put that away.

55:17.280 --> 55:18.759
You gotta learn those times tables.

55:18.760 --> 55:21.199
Oh, he's just working
on addition, Dad.

55:21.200 --> 55:23.119
Yeah. He's six.

55:23.120 --> 55:24.399
I know my times tables.

55:24.400 --> 55:26.359
Yeah, there you go. We got
someone who knows them there.

55:26.360 --> 55:30.581
Good. Study hard.
Don't become an actor.

55:31.400 --> 55:32.879
Well, maybe I'll take
the kids outside.

55:32.880 --> 55:34.359
No, sweetie. Don't, no, no,
no one's going anywhere.

55:34.360 --> 55:37.039
Yeah, I think maybe
it's time to take them.

55:37.040 --> 55:39.919
It's fine when you're
playing around in college.

55:39.920 --> 55:43.264
But sooner or later you have
to provide for your family.

55:43.360 --> 55:45.669
You're gonna need those times tables.

55:45.880 --> 55:47.999
Well, maybe Tucker will have a wife

55:48.000 --> 55:50.279
who loves him and supports him.

55:50.280 --> 55:52.919
And will remind him of the answer
if he occasionally forgets.

55:52.920 --> 55:56.390
Maybe he'll marry someone
that enables his fantasies.

55:56.640 --> 55:59.999
Lets him sit around waiting
for a dream to come true

56:00.000 --> 56:03.788
while his children sit dumbfounded
by the edge of a muddy pool.

56:04.400 --> 56:08.302
Grace can't even swim,
for God's sakes.

56:10.760 --> 56:14.679
Um, grandpa,
I found something for you.

56:14.680 --> 56:16.079
Something that you're gonna need.

56:16.080 --> 56:19.470
What, my angel, my hope?

56:21.880 --> 56:24.759
What the hell am I gonna
do with welder's goggles?

56:24.760 --> 56:27.547
Well, here, put them on.

56:31.200 --> 56:32.999
You look good.

56:33.000 --> 56:36.959
Now, when you head into the white
light, you won't have to squint.

56:36.960 --> 56:41.146
So you can find Grandma.

57:59.880 --> 58:01.359
Guys, that was fantastic.

58:01.360 --> 58:02.861
Why don't you take a break?

58:03.920 --> 58:06.399
Terrific job.

58:06.400 --> 58:08.239
It was beautiful, you guys.

58:08.240 --> 58:10.469
- Really nice.
- Thanks.

58:11.320 --> 58:12.919
I'm not here to convert.

58:12.920 --> 58:15.263
Good, 'cause I've
already met my quota.

58:16.320 --> 58:18.185
Have a seat.

58:20.440 --> 58:24.399
You know, I was kosher
until I was 13.

58:24.400 --> 58:25.679
Really?

58:25.680 --> 58:26.919
Yeah.

58:26.920 --> 58:31.948
Yeah. My father told me that I was
officially a man at my Bar Mitzvah.

58:32.040 --> 58:34.439
So I told him that, as a man,

58:34.440 --> 58:37.079
I wanted to have a bacon
double cheeseburger.

58:39.000 --> 58:41.628
I think I saw his head explode.

58:41.800 --> 58:44.159
But to his credit, he let me eat

58:44.160 --> 58:47.311
whatever I wanted outside the house.

58:47.920 --> 58:50.991
I think I impressed
him with my logic.

58:53.640 --> 58:56.302
What brings you to temple, Aidan?

58:57.240 --> 58:58.959
When we were kids, my brother and I

58:58.960 --> 59:00.639
used to pretend we were these

59:00.640 --> 59:03.620
superhero space-men.

59:04.800 --> 59:07.039
We'd go out to the
woods behind our house

59:07.040 --> 59:10.279
and pretend it was
this mystical planet

59:10.280 --> 59:13.590
and we were the only ones
who could save everybody.

59:15.600 --> 59:18.706
But I've been thinking
about that a lot lately.

59:19.240 --> 59:23.839
Remembering those fantasies
for the first time in, like,

59:23.840 --> 59:25.479
14 years.

59:25.480 --> 59:27.186
What do you think it means?

59:27.520 --> 59:30.479
I don't know. And I'm even
embarrassed to say this out loud,

59:30.480 --> 59:33.506
but if I can't say it to you,
I can't say it to anybody.

59:34.840 --> 59:36.910
Do you think

59:37.560 --> 59:42.065
God is trying to tell me something?

59:43.200 --> 59:45.679
Trying to guide me in some way?

59:45.680 --> 59:50.185
And if you say He works in mysterious
ways, I will run out that door.

59:51.000 --> 59:55.869
Do you feel any spiritual
connection at all to anything?

59:56.000 --> 59:57.865
Infinity.

01:00:01.000 --> 01:00:03.279
Looking up at the sky with my kids

01:00:03.280 --> 01:00:06.879
and trying to explain to them
that it goes on forever.

01:00:06.880 --> 01:00:10.509
I do feel a spirituality in that.

01:00:14.040 --> 01:00:15.959
Could that be God?

01:00:15.960 --> 01:00:18.861
God can be whatever
you want him to be.

01:00:19.440 --> 01:00:22.039
You're getting tangled in semantics.

01:00:22.040 --> 01:00:24.919
Try not to get caught up in the
God who wants you to be kosher,

01:00:24.920 --> 01:00:27.741
and the God who wants
you to study the Torah.

01:00:28.360 --> 01:00:31.719
Start with God as
the infinite universe,

01:00:31.720 --> 01:00:33.279
and imagine that that force may be

01:00:33.280 --> 01:00:35.399
trying desperately to guide you

01:00:35.400 --> 01:00:39.905
through the most challenging
part of your life.

01:00:40.120 --> 01:00:44.750
Even if it has to appear to you
in the form of a space-man

01:00:45.560 --> 01:00:47.630
to get you to listen.

01:00:58.840 --> 01:01:01.519
Why does Grandpa have baby jellyfish?

01:01:01.520 --> 01:01:03.319
Those aren't jellyfish, buddy.

01:01:03.320 --> 01:01:06.879
Believe it or not,
those are contact lenses.

01:01:06.880 --> 01:01:10.999
Your grandpa saved all the
contact lenses he ever wore.

01:01:11.000 --> 01:01:12.119
Why?

01:01:12.120 --> 01:01:14.439
He said he just couldn't
bear to throw them out

01:01:14.440 --> 01:01:16.942
'cause it's everything he ever saw.

01:01:17.240 --> 01:01:18.999
It's weird, right?

01:01:19.000 --> 01:01:21.559
I know, but it's kinda
good-weird. I like it.

01:01:21.560 --> 01:01:23.679
Well, he must have
seen a lot of stuff.

01:01:23.680 --> 01:01:25.799
He did. If you think about it,
all those years,

01:01:25.800 --> 01:01:29.079
all the things that he saw with
his eyes through those lenses.

01:01:29.080 --> 01:01:32.439
Also, before he retired,
he was a microbiology professor.

01:01:32.440 --> 01:01:33.759
What's that?

01:01:33.760 --> 01:01:35.199
That's someone who studies things

01:01:35.200 --> 01:01:37.359
you can only see with a microscope.

01:01:37.360 --> 01:01:41.103
So, really, really,
really tiny things. Hey!

01:01:41.120 --> 01:01:42.879
I know the albums are fascinating,

01:01:42.880 --> 01:01:45.359
but I could use a little help
getting this place set up

01:01:45.360 --> 01:01:48.340
so it's nice and cozy for
when Grandpa comes home.

01:01:48.400 --> 01:01:51.380
So, if Grandpa's dying,
then why is he coming home?

01:01:51.440 --> 01:01:55.919
Because we don't want Grandpa
to be alone in a scary hospital.

01:01:55.920 --> 01:01:58.959
We want him to come home and
be with his family, be with us.

01:01:58.960 --> 01:02:03.101
So we're making him all cozy so
he's happy when he meets God?

01:02:04.480 --> 01:02:05.981
Yeah.

01:02:09.800 --> 01:02:12.319
Whoa! When did Grandpa
have this cool car?

01:02:12.320 --> 01:02:14.879
Look at that thing.

01:02:14.880 --> 01:02:19.669
That, my friends, is a '62 Cadillac.
Look at those fins.

01:02:19.920 --> 01:02:22.468
Look how happy he was, huh?

01:02:22.680 --> 01:02:24.239
Why, this was taken at a dealership.

01:02:24.240 --> 01:02:26.151
He could never afford that car.

01:02:26.360 --> 01:02:27.599
That sucks.

01:02:27.600 --> 01:02:29.226
It does suck.

01:02:29.680 --> 01:02:31.511
It's cool.

01:02:34.680 --> 01:02:37.679
Hello. Welcome to Aston Martin.

01:02:37.680 --> 01:02:41.679
Hello. Um, my name is Marco

01:02:41.680 --> 01:02:46.310
and I work for Sean "Puff
Daddy" "Dirty Money" Combs.

01:02:46.680 --> 01:02:48.599
Um, these are Puffy's children,

01:02:48.600 --> 01:02:51.199
and he's asked me to
come in and test drive

01:02:51.200 --> 01:02:54.590
the new Aston Martin DB9 Volante.

01:02:55.680 --> 01:02:56.839
Can I talk to you for a second?

01:02:56.840 --> 01:02:58.119
Of course.

01:02:58.120 --> 01:02:59.319
Please, come right here.

01:02:59.320 --> 01:03:00.901
Be good, children.

01:03:01.600 --> 01:03:02.879
I know what you're thinking.

01:03:02.880 --> 01:03:05.428
"Why are Puffy's kids white?"

01:03:05.680 --> 01:03:07.439
Valid question.

01:03:07.440 --> 01:03:10.519
Well, so many celebrities were
going and adopting black children.

01:03:10.520 --> 01:03:11.919
- You know what he went and did?
- Mmm-mmm.

01:03:11.920 --> 01:03:15.549
He went to Switzerland and adopted
these two skim-milk popsicles.

01:03:15.920 --> 01:03:18.359
Tucker! Do not.
Tucker, it's not funny.

01:03:18.360 --> 01:03:19.799
I know what you're trying to do.

01:03:19.800 --> 01:03:20.879
You do?

01:03:20.880 --> 01:03:22.479
Do you know how many
people walk in here

01:03:22.480 --> 01:03:24.719
and try to sweet-talk their way into

01:03:24.720 --> 01:03:26.559
test-driving one of these bad boys?

01:03:26.560 --> 01:03:29.904
- So annoying.
- Hey! I never fall for it.

01:03:34.160 --> 01:03:36.469
But I can see your daughter's sick.

01:03:37.240 --> 01:03:40.719
So, you know what?
I'm gonna make an exception.

01:03:40.720 --> 01:03:42.199
And you don't even
look good in the wig.

01:03:42.200 --> 01:03:43.559
So take it off, like, seriously.

01:03:43.560 --> 01:03:45.039
- No way.
- It's my wig.

01:03:45.040 --> 01:03:47.110
She is sick, isn't she?

01:03:49.160 --> 01:03:51.199
Have some respect.

01:03:51.200 --> 01:03:53.031
- So sick.
- Mmm...

01:03:53.400 --> 01:03:55.919
Okay, attendance.

01:03:55.920 --> 01:03:57.239
- Grace.
- Here!

01:03:57.240 --> 01:03:59.504
- Tucker.
- Here.

01:03:59.680 --> 01:04:01.759
- What's your name?
- Anthony.

01:04:01.760 --> 01:04:03.119
Anthony's here, too, Dad.

01:04:03.120 --> 01:04:05.359
All right, Anthony.
Welcome to our classroom.

01:04:05.360 --> 01:04:07.519
Now, kids, unless
you're on the Autobahn,

01:04:07.520 --> 01:04:10.079
you're never gonna get a
car like this up to speed.

01:04:10.080 --> 01:04:11.879
So in a city like LA,

01:04:11.880 --> 01:04:13.559
it's really about what it sounds like

01:04:13.560 --> 01:04:15.239
when you floor it from a full stop.

01:04:15.240 --> 01:04:17.559
Yes, but, kids, we're on
Robertson Boulevard.

01:04:17.560 --> 01:04:19.199
So there will be no flooring it

01:04:19.200 --> 01:04:21.119
from a full stop, will there be?

01:04:21.120 --> 01:04:23.588
- No, sir.
- Thank you.

01:05:07.640 --> 01:05:09.471
Did I scare you?

01:05:10.840 --> 01:05:12.759
I thought if I ever
saw you here alone,

01:05:12.760 --> 01:05:15.183
you'd be putting a
pillow over my face.

01:05:15.320 --> 01:05:16.999
I looked.

01:05:17.000 --> 01:05:18.919
You're lying on the
only two in the room.

01:05:20.160 --> 01:05:21.759
I've been watching the paramedics

01:05:21.760 --> 01:05:23.239
come and go for the last half-hour.

01:05:23.240 --> 01:05:25.639
And every few minutes
they race in at full speed

01:05:25.640 --> 01:05:27.639
doing everything they can
to save someone's life

01:05:27.640 --> 01:05:30.359
and then a few minutes later,

01:05:30.360 --> 01:05:33.511
they all walk outside
and smoke cigarettes.

01:05:36.360 --> 01:05:39.799
You never really think about
death until you're here.

01:05:40.880 --> 01:05:45.119
Chemicals pumping into your veins
while you watch Maury Povich.

01:05:45.120 --> 01:05:47.941
I'm unclear which one
is killing me faster.

01:05:49.160 --> 01:05:50.599
Can I offer you some saline?

01:05:50.600 --> 01:05:53.439
I'm glad to see you're
keeping your sense of humor.

01:05:53.440 --> 01:05:55.544
What else am I supposed to do?

01:05:55.920 --> 01:05:58.719
Eventually things get tragic enough

01:05:58.720 --> 01:06:00.904
and they circle back to comedy.

01:06:01.360 --> 01:06:03.703
Yeah.

01:06:06.200 --> 01:06:09.385
You know, I don't think
I ever told you this,

01:06:11.400 --> 01:06:16.030
but when I lost my sister, you were
the most helpful person to me.

01:06:16.040 --> 01:06:18.144
- Really?
- Yeah.

01:06:18.280 --> 01:06:23.183
I mean, I'm glad if I was, but I
don't even remember what I said.

01:06:24.560 --> 01:06:26.391
You said,

01:06:27.280 --> 01:06:30.399
"Nothing in life will call upon
us to be more courageous

01:06:30.400 --> 01:06:33.359
"than facing the fact that it ends.

01:06:33.360 --> 01:06:36.989
"But on the other side of
heartbreak is wisdom."

01:06:38.200 --> 01:06:39.439
I said that?

01:06:39.440 --> 01:06:41.101
Yeah.

01:06:41.920 --> 01:06:43.751
That was good advice.

01:06:45.080 --> 01:06:49.346
And now here I am,
a shiva waiting to happen.

01:06:49.600 --> 01:06:53.104
Well, the wisdom that came out for me

01:06:54.200 --> 01:06:58.421
was that the things left
unsaid stay with us forever.

01:07:00.560 --> 01:07:03.279
I wish nothing more

01:07:03.280 --> 01:07:06.386
than if I could tell my
sister how much I loved her

01:07:06.640 --> 01:07:09.507
and that I always idolized her.

01:07:09.920 --> 01:07:11.359
But we never said those things.

01:07:11.360 --> 01:07:14.067
We just weren't like that.

01:07:16.960 --> 01:07:20.589
And suddenly one day she's gone.

01:07:26.680 --> 01:07:30.519
And I have all these things to say,

01:07:30.520 --> 01:07:32.306
but no one to say them to.

01:07:34.480 --> 01:07:37.319
Both my boys know how I feel.

01:07:37.320 --> 01:07:39.504
Are you sure, Gabe?

01:07:46.880 --> 01:07:50.145
I told them I wanted to retire.

01:07:51.320 --> 01:07:53.151
I lied.

01:07:55.360 --> 01:07:57.624
They pushed me out.

01:08:01.160 --> 01:08:04.584
'Cause I wasn't keeping
up with technology.

01:08:07.600 --> 01:08:10.421
Don't let anyone push them out.

01:08:10.920 --> 01:08:12.999
Have you told them this?

01:08:13.000 --> 01:08:15.025
What is this?

01:08:15.360 --> 01:08:17.862
Is this an intervention?

01:08:17.960 --> 01:08:20.479
Did you come here to tell
me how I failed as a father?

01:08:20.479 --> 01:08:22.140
No!

01:08:24.520 --> 01:08:28.627
Not at all. You've raised
two incredible boys, Gabe.

01:08:29.240 --> 01:08:31.078
They may not have quick answers

01:08:31.080 --> 01:08:33.947
or awards on their mantles.

01:08:35.040 --> 01:08:38.384
In fact, neither one
of them has a mantle.

01:08:39.000 --> 01:08:41.264
But they're incredible,

01:08:43.520 --> 01:08:46.466
with big, sensitive hearts.

01:08:47.720 --> 01:08:49.439
And right now they need to know

01:08:49.439 --> 01:08:51.863
how much their father loves them.

01:08:56.640 --> 01:09:00.747
Barbara used to help you with
the hard part of parenting, right?

01:09:04.160 --> 01:09:06.707
She made everyone around her happy.

01:09:09.399 --> 01:09:11.982
She just brought out the best in me.

01:09:19.359 --> 01:09:21.759
I think if she were here right
now she'd tell you that

01:09:21.760 --> 01:09:25.548
your boys will remember this
time for the rest of their lives.

01:09:30.040 --> 01:09:33.020
It will shape who they are as men.

01:09:41.080 --> 01:09:44.151
You're gonna make a great
matriarch one day.

01:09:51.760 --> 01:09:54.945
I already am a great matriarch, Gabe.

01:10:05.840 --> 01:10:08.468
At least I'm working on it.

01:10:13.600 --> 01:10:18.799
Today, we are going to Mr. Miyagi
the shit out of this fence.

01:10:18.800 --> 01:10:20.159
Who's Mr. Miyagi?

01:10:20.160 --> 01:10:22.639
Mr. Miyagi is an older Asian man

01:10:22.640 --> 01:10:24.824
that taught me many life lessons.

01:10:25.000 --> 01:10:28.079
The point is I'm sick of
looking at this fence.

01:10:28.080 --> 01:10:29.599
Today we're gonna fix it.

01:10:29.600 --> 01:10:30.959
Tucker, where's your drill?

01:10:30.960 --> 01:10:33.303
- It's under my pillow.
- Please go get it.

01:10:33.480 --> 01:10:36.301
- Whoo-hoo!
- Okay, Grace, come up here.

01:10:37.760 --> 01:10:39.039
Hop on the diving board.

01:10:39.040 --> 01:10:40.666
Okay.

01:10:41.000 --> 01:10:44.199
You are going to recite this poem

01:10:44.200 --> 01:10:46.384
while Tucker and I work on the fence.

01:10:46.600 --> 01:10:48.399
Then we'll switch.

01:10:48.400 --> 01:10:49.839
This is weird.

01:10:49.840 --> 01:10:54.186
Think of it as a prayer you're
not expecting anyone to answer.

01:10:54.680 --> 01:10:57.879
All right, Tuck, good.
Come over here. Put the drill down.

01:10:57.880 --> 01:10:59.999
We're gonna use it later
when we put 'em back up.

01:11:00.000 --> 01:11:02.519
Come over here with this crowbar.

01:11:02.520 --> 01:11:06.119
And the point is to jam it in
here and then use your leverage.

01:11:06.120 --> 01:11:07.719
Slide your arms down. Yeah!

01:11:07.720 --> 01:11:09.599
Oh! You're a natural at this.

01:11:09.600 --> 01:11:13.229
Next up, we're gonna
re-plaster that pool.

01:11:15.040 --> 01:11:18.479
"Something there is that
doesn't love a wall

01:11:18.480 --> 01:11:22.039
"That sends the
frozen-ground-swell under it

01:11:22.040 --> 01:11:25.384
"And spills the upper
boulders in the sun

01:11:25.920 --> 01:11:28.559
"I let my neighbor
know beyond the hill

01:11:28.560 --> 01:11:31.159
"And on a day we
meet to walk the line

01:11:31.160 --> 01:11:34.391
"And set the wall
between us once again

01:11:35.680 --> 01:11:38.319
"Before I built a
wall I'd ask to know

01:11:38.320 --> 01:11:40.743
"What I was walling in or walling out

01:11:40.840 --> 01:11:43.707
"And to whom I was
like to give offense

01:11:44.760 --> 01:11:48.343
"Something there is
that doesn't love a wall

